docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:93:ADR means Architecture Decision Record. An ADR is a short document that records an important architecture decision, the alternatives considered, the chosen option, and the consequences.
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:97:The system or assisting agent should actively point out when a decision appears ADR-worthy. It should not silently create ADR bureaucracy for routine work, but it should tell the maintainer when a choice has long-term architectural consequences and would benefit from an ADR.
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:111:Status: proposed | accepted | superseded
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:137:- When a proposed change affects project architecture, public CLI semantics, state-machine behavior, repair strategy, release workflow, evidence policy, capability boundaries, or long-term agent behavior, the assistant should explicitly say whether an ADR is recommended.
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:138:- If an ADR is recommended, the assistant should explain the decision to preserve, the alternatives that matter, and whether the ADR should be created now or deferred.
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:139:- If an ADR is not recommended, the assistant should continue with the normal documentation, tests, and implementation path without adding extra process.
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:140:- The maintainer decides whether to create the ADR. The assistant should not treat ADR creation as automatic approval to expand scope.
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:144:- ADRs should explain why, not merely what;
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:145:- ADRs should not replace tests or documentation coverage;
docs/ideas/GOVERNED_WORKFLOW_PATTERNS.md:146:- superseded ADRs should remain in place and point to the successor;
