docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:5:Review policy: review before v0.4.0 planning, roadmap reshaping, UI polish, CLI polish, migration automation, or advisory automation changes
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:17:- deterministic governance is already solid (`doctor`, `check-docs`, `doc-mesh-audit`, release checks);
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:23:External reviews of v0.3.12 are directionally useful, but they should not be treated as proof that the project is already finished. Grok correctly identifies the disciplined Pattern Advisor MVP and its boundary control. Gemini correctly emphasizes the didactic and process-control character of the project, but some of that didactic guidance predates v0.3.12 and should not be over-attributed to this release.
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:27:The project is no longer an early MVP. It is already useful for a disciplined maintainer. The remaining gap is professional polish: installation, onboarding, command discoverability, recovery guidance, and user-facing documentation.
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:37:The project should be considered a professional single-user tool when one maintainer can do the following without deep repo knowledge:
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:53:v0.3.13 should be a small tactical release. Its purpose is to reduce friction discovered during the v0.3.12 release cycle before starting a larger v0.4.0 milestone.
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:69:### v0.4.0: Professional Polish milestone
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:71:v0.4.0 should be the first deliberately polished milestone. It should not be a feature explosion. It should focus on three pillars.
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:83:- keep the local cockpit action layer as the shared backend for CLI adapters, terminal menus, and a later Tkinter cockpit;
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:90:- no automatic command selection based on vague context;
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:119:- add a MkDocs-based documentation site or prepare the documentation structure for it;
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:131:Only after v0.4.0 professional polish should the project expand advisory intelligence.
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:142:v0.5.0 should be the point where the tool feels complete for one serious maintainer:
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:148:- a documentation site exists or the docs are structured as if they could be published immediately;
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:167:4. Pattern catalog growth after CLI polish.
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:180:The following rules should remain stable through v0.4 and v0.5:
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:196:Start with v0.3.13 as a short stabilizing strategy-to-implementation bridge:
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:201:4. decide whether `./ns release` should exist and exactly what it may do;
docs/strategy/V0.4_PROFESSIONAL_SINGLE_USER_STRATEGY.md:212:The next strategic step is therefore not Pattern Advisor expansion and not broader release automation. The next step is a thin local Tkinter cockpit over the existing safe action layer, with visible status, command output, latest command report, latest terminal log, clean-state checks, and gate buttons. Shell-to-Python portability remains part of this direction: GUI and CLI adapters should call explicit Python-backed helpers or argument-vector actions, not synthesize fragile shell snippets.
docs/workflow/COMMUNICATION_ARTIFACT_GC.md:5:Communication, handoff, terminal, and command-run artifacts must not accumulate without classification. They also must not be removed by ad-hoc shell deletion. The project therefore uses a central artifact registry in `.agentic/communication_artifacts.yaml` and a deterministic garbage-collector workflow.
docs/workflow/COMMUNICATION_ARTIFACT_GC.md:24:The registry covers the existing temporary and communication artifact classes currently used by the repository: `/tmp/agentic-project-kit-*.log`, `docs/reports/terminal/*.log`, `docs/reports/terminal/LATEST_TERMINAL_LOG.txt`, `docs/reports/command_runs/*.md`, `.agentic/commands/inbox/*`, and `.agentic/commands/current.*`.
docs/workflow/COMMUNICATION_ARTIFACT_GC.md:31:- `.agentic/commands/current.yaml` and `.agentic/commands/current.sh` are treated as transient runner compatibility files.
docs/workflow/COMMUNICATION_ARTIFACT_GC.md:37:- Local `/tmp/agentic-project-kit-*.log` files are the only TTL-based local tmp-log class currently handled by the GC.
docs/workflow/COMMUNICATION_ARTIFACT_GC.md:39:- `./ns artifact-gc --tmp-logs --execute` may delete only expired, non-symlink `/tmp/agentic-project-kit-*.log` files directly under `/tmp`.
docs/workflow/COMMUNICATION_ARTIFACT_GC.md:44:```bash
docs/workflow/CONTROL_MODEL.md:17:5. Commit, push, PR, merge, or release only after the preceding state is valid
docs/workflow/CONTROL_MODEL.md:20:Dependent tests, gates, commits, pushes, PR creation, merges, tags, and releases must not run after a failed core step.
docs/workflow/CONTROL_MODEL.md:55:A failure state must not be followed by tests, gates, commits, pushes, PR creation, merges, tags, releases, or finalization.
docs/workflow/CONTROL_MODEL.md:65:- Treating already merged or superseded finalization branches as hard failures
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:14:- `./ns handoff-show` prints a compact summary.
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:15:- `./ns handoff-check` validates required fields, active rule ids, superseded rule metadata, and failure-pattern prevention notes.
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:20:Rules use `active`, `superseded`, or `historical` status. Generated handoff prompts include active rules by default and must not present superseded or historical rules as binding instructions.
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:24:The handoff state references `.agentic/no_copy_terminal_policy.yaml`. A normal PASS handoff should therefore rely on committed/pushed logs and reports; manual terminal paste is reserved for failure or unavailable evidence.
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:32:Terminal blocks pasted into an interactive shell must never terminate that shell. Do not use `exit`, `logout`, `kill`, or top-level `exec` in chat-pasted blocks. A pasted block must report `### RESULT: PASS ###`, `### RESULT: FAIL ###`, or `### RESULT: PENDING ###` and then return to the prompt. Use exit codes only inside saved scripts executed as child processes.
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:44:`safe_state.commit` records the last substantive work state by default, not necessarily the newest administrative refresh merge on `main`.
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:46:This prevents endless refresh loops: a PR that only refreshes `.agentic/handoff_state.yaml` does not require another refresh PR just because it produced a newer merge commit.
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:48:Use `safe_state.semantics: last_substantive_work_state` for this mode. Administrative refresh PR numbers may be recorded under `safe_state.administrative_refresh_prs`.
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:50:## Planning-state freshness rule
docs/workflow/HANDOFF_STATE.md:54:`./ns state-freshness-check` must reject stale current-state fragments such as obsolete released-version claims, outdated next-step instructions, or a handoff YAML version that disagrees with current status documents. This rule exists because stale planning files caused repeated wrong-command, wrong-path, and wrong-priority drift.
docs/workflow/NO_COPY_TERMINAL_EVIDENCE.md:15:- Normal FAIL handoff must use f and repo-backed evidence, typically docs/reports/command_runs/LATEST_COMMAND_RUN.txt plus the referenced terminal log. Manual terminal output is required only when FAIL evidence is unavailable, logging is broken, the process aborted, the terminal was lost, kill -9 occurred, pushed evidence is unavailable, or the user explicitly asks for pasted output.
docs/workflow/NO_COPY_TERMINAL_EVIDENCE.md:20:For repo-backed agent commands, `docs/reports/command_runs/LATEST_COMMAND_RUN.txt` is the canonical first read after `d` or `f`. The referenced command report records the outcome, exit code, branch, script hash, and terminal-log path. A normal FAIL must still leave remote evidence; otherwise the workflow is broken and must be repaired.
docs/workflow/PARAMETERIZED_ACTIONS.md:10:The MVP is intentionally read-only. It exposes action metadata through `agentic-kit actions list`, `agentic-kit actions show <id>`, `./ns action-list`, and `./ns action-show <id>`.
docs/workflow/PARAMETERIZED_ACTIONS.md:17:- GUI/Cockpit controls should consume these action specs instead of assembling raw shell snippets.
docs/workflow/PRE_GUI_EXECUTION_HARDENING.md:17:A workflow must not commit, push, merge, tag, or publish after a required targeted test, full gate, or postcondition check has failed. A failed gate must produce a failing final summary.
docs/workflow/PRE_GUI_EXECUTION_HARDENING.md:25:Patch generation must avoid fragile nested Python-in-shell or Python-in-Python quoting. Prefer typed work orders, direct file rewrites, small checked scripts, or repository-owned patch helpers.
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:5:Instead of pasting terminal blocks into the shell, the repository stores the current command in:
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:8:- `.agentic/commands/current.sh`
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:14:3. validates `current.sh` with `sh -n`,
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:18:7. commits and pushes the command report and terminal log.
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:39:`./ns agent-next` is the preferred command for routine no-copy handoff. It pulls the current branch, expects exactly one complete pending command pair under `.agentic/commands/inbox/`, copies that pair to the transient `current.yaml` and `current.sh` compatibility path, executes it through `agent-run`, then removes the transient current files.
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:41:Pending command files use matching names, for example `.agentic/commands/inbox/example.yaml` and `.agentic/commands/inbox/example.sh`. Multiple complete pending commands are refused with `FAIL_AMBIGUOUS_COMMANDS`.
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:50:- no transient `.agentic/commands/current.sh`
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:58:Every `./ns agent-run` or `./ns agent-next` run writes `docs/reports/command_runs/LATEST_COMMAND_RUN.txt`. The file points to the newest command-run report under `docs/reports/command_runs/`. After the user replies `d` for PASS or `f` for normal FAIL, the next agent must read this pointer first, then the referenced report, then the terminal log referenced by that report. Copy-and-paste is reserved for terminal crashes, authentication/network failure, or missing remote evidence.
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:66:`./ns agent-next` distinguishes normal command failure from workflow-level hard failures. Pull failures, ambiguous pending commands, upload/postcondition failures, authentication/network problems, and missing remote evidence are hard failures. The visible footer must print `### AGENT-NEXT RESULT: HARD-FAIL ###` and `reply=paste-output` for these cases. A normal command exit failure remains `FAIL` with `reply=f`, and no pending command remains `NO-COMMAND` with `reply=ask-agent-to-queue-command`.
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:70:`./ns command-inbox-check` validates the repo-backed queue before local execution. It accepts an empty inbox or exactly one complete `.yaml`/`.sh` pair, rejects orphan files, rejects multiple complete pending commands, validates required metadata and safety classes, runs `sh -n`, and blocks known unsafe command-script fragments such as heredocs, branch switches, pull commands, logout, kill, and top-level exec usage.
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:74:`agent-run` treats a terminal log whose last result marker is `### RESULT: FAIL ###` as `FAIL_COMMAND`, even if the shell process exits with code 0. This prevents evidence finalization or wrapper layers from masking failed command scripts as `PASS_EXECUTED`.
docs/workflow/REPO_COMMAND_RUNNER.md:78:`agent-run` report creation must not crash if `.agentic/commands/current.sh` is removed during command execution. In that case the script SHA256 field is recorded as `missing` so the runner can still write durable command-run evidence and return a deterministic outcome.
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:5:The terminal-log workflow must optimize for deterministic quality, not speed. Repeated logging, dirty-state, false-PASS, or handoff failures are product defects and must be addressed with helpers, guards, tests, and documentation instead of relying on manual discipline.
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:16:- The terminal log must be staged, committed, and pushed together with the code/docs changes from that run.
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:19:- A log file must not be written again after the commit that is supposed to contain it.
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:24:A successful run should end with:
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:28:git status --short
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:32:If the final `git status --short` shows a modified terminal log, the commit is incomplete.
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:39:- `./ns terminal-upload`: failure-handoff helper that commits and pushes only terminal-log artifacts.
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:44:Commands executed through `./ns run-logged` must not use plain `test -z "$(git status --short)"` as a cleanliness gate, because `run-logged` necessarily updates `docs/reports/terminal/LATEST_TERMINAL_LOG.txt` and creates a terminal log.
docs/workflow/TERMINAL_LOG_HANDOFF_RULE.md:54:Do not commit a repository log file while the current process is still writing to it. Long scripts must tee into a temporary log outside `docs/reports/terminal/`, then finalize the completed log into `docs/reports/terminal/*.log` with `./ns terminal-finalize <tmp-log> <name>` before staging, committing, and pushing. The finalized log must contain an explicit `### RESULT: PASS ###`, `### RESULT: FAIL ###`, or `### RESULT: PENDING ###` marker.
docs/workflow/TYPED_WORK_ORDER_EVIDENCE_CONTRACT.md:17:## Minimal YAML shape
docs/workflow/TYPED_WORK_ORDER_EVIDENCE_CONTRACT.md:34:The future Tkinter GUI must not infer success from raw shell text. It must display structured typed Work Order result fields and evidence validation state.
docs/workflow/WORK_ORDERS.md:14:- `agentic-kit work-order show <id>` displays the selected work order.
docs/workflow/WORK_ORDERS.md:23:A work order is not allowed to report success by printing its own PASS marker. The runner owns PASS/FAIL result markers. A work order may only pass after its command returns success and the required contract checks have passed.
docs/workflow/WORK_ORDERS.md:49:Add checked work-order templates for common read-only gates first. Mutating Git, PR, release, DOI, and finalize flows should use parameterized action specs plus deterministic validators before execution.
docs/workflow/WORK_ORDER_PREPARE.md:8:`work-order prepare` turns versioned repo templates into concrete work orders. This reduces fragile chat-authored shell blocks and makes commands, gates, logs, and postconditions testable before execution.
docs/workflow/WORK_ORDER_PREPARE.md:12:Routine workflows should be expressed as repo-backed work orders instead of long ad-hoc terminal blocks. Generated work orders must pass the work order contract before they are executed.
